0","1130":"1130","1184":"1184","1183":"1183","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1233":"1233","1211":"1211","about 1148":"about 1148","about 1155":"about 1155","of Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France","Bampton, Devon, England":"Bampton, Devon, England","Hambye, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France","of Drax, Yorkshire, England":"Drax, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Paynel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Payne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Paynel , Seigneur de Servon, Archdeacon of d’Avranches was born about 1148, in Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France, his father, Foulques Paynel of Bampton, was 30 and his mother, Lesceline de Subligny, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Aliénor de   Vitre. He died in 1184, in Drax, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 37."},"et":{"about 1148–1184":"umbes 1148–1184","1135–1216":"1135–1216","1148–1184":"1148–1184","1150–1215":"1150–1215","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1160–1211":"1160–1211","1158–1233":"1158–1233","1183–Male":"1183–Surnud","1120–1182":"1120–1182","1130–1150":"1130–1150","about 1150":"umbes 1150","about 1183":"umbes 1183","about 1182":"umbes 1182","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1184":"1184","1183":"1183","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1233":"1233","1211":"1211","about 1148":"umbes 1148","about 1155":"umbes 1155","of Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bampton, Devon, England":"Bampton, Devon, England","Hambye, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","of Drax, Yorkshire, England":"Drax, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1148–1184":"noin 1148–1184","1135–1216":"1135–1216","1148–1184":"1148–1184","1150–1215":"1150–1215","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1158–Male":"1158–Kuollut","1160–1211":"1160–1211","1158–1233":"1158–1233","1183–Male":"1183–Kuollut","1120–1182":"1120–1182","1130–1150":"1130–1150","about 1150":"noin 1150","about 1183":"noin 1183","about 1182":"noin 1182","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1184":"1184","1183":"1183","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1233":"1233","1211":"1211","about 1148":"noin 